This or That?

Roberta Rocca

23/04/2018

Analysis of data on crosslinguistic study on semantic preferences in demonstratives use. Data preprocessing performed separately for each dataset. Markdowns available in the Preprocessing subfolder.

Run: Sys.setlocale(category = LC_ALL, locale = da_dk.utf-8) Sys.setlocale(category = LC_MESSAGES, locale = da_dk.utf-8) For a correct visualization of the Danish characters

Analysis

Includes logistic regression using categorical predictors per each dataset, as well as cumulative analysis. Also includes parametrized version using animacy, harmfulness and size scores. Loading the dataset with information on experimental words

library(readr)
library(lme4)
library(dplyr)

# BNC
freq_bnc <- read_tsv('freq_bnc.txt')
# Danish
freq_dk <- read_tsv('freq_dk.txt')
freq_dk$Freq <- freq_dk$Freq / 2570.805
#Italian
freq_it <- read_tsv('freq_it.txt')
freq_it$Freq <- freq_it$Freq / 5864.496
# Merge all the frequency data in a single dataset.
freq <- rbind(freq_bnc[, 2:3], freq_dk)
freq <- rbind(freq, freq_it)

Proportion of proximal demonstratives across experimental variables for each of the languages and experiments

Stats: mixed-effects logistic regression for each of the experiments. Same model used for all languages, fixed effects structure including all the experimental factors and full interaction structure. Random effects structure include random intercept for ID. More complicated random effects structure fitted in the overall model.

Experiment 1

# Model all data, add fixed effect of language and interactions
model_1 <- glmer(data = subset(data_all, !(ExpNr == 2)), 
                 factor(Demonstrative) ~ Animate * Size * Harm * Lang + (1|ID), 
                 family = 'binomial', 
                 glmerControl(optimizer="bobyqa", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 100000)))

Compare previous model for Italian with one taking into account the soundness of the coupling between noun and distal demonstratives

it_corr <-glmer(data = data_IT, 
                factor(Demonstrative) ~ Animate * Size * Harm + Incorrect + Incorrect:Animate + Incorrect:Harm + Incorrect:Size + (1|ID), 
                family = 'binomial', 
                glmerControl(optimizer="bobyqa", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 100000)))

# Compare the model with the previous one
anova(it_log1, it_corr)

Parametric version of the analysis

Here we look at whether the effects found in the logistic analysis are confirmed when using 1-5 scores for size and harmfulness. Scores are taken from the Sudre et al. (2012) database for experiment one, whereas for experiment two, scores are predicted using SVR on GloVe word vectors to predict 1-5 scores. Models are tuned and trained on words from Sudre et al. (2012).

# All parametric model
all_par <- glmer(data = subset(data_all, !(ExpNr == 1 & Lang == 'IT')), 
                 Demonstrative ~ Animate + as.numeric(SizeScore) + as.numeric(HarmScore) + Animate:as.numeric(SizeScore) + Animate:as.numeric(HarmScore)+ (1|ID), 
                 family = 'binomial', 
                 glmerControl(optimizer="bobyqa", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 100000)))

Frequency

Are there systematic differences in frequency between levels of our experimental variables, which might confound the results? We looked up word frequencies in all of the language, plotted it and ran statistical tests. First step: read in the frequency data for English: BNC data Data extracted from http://ucrel.lancs.ac.uk/bncfreq/, updated to 2001. Values refer to rounded lemma frequency per million token.

        panel.grid.minor = element_line(color = 'grey', linetype = 'dotted')) +
  geom_text_repel(aes(label = NounEng))
